132
00:05:26,100 --> 00:05:28,495
So the same is true for a streaming event.

133
00:05:28,495 --> 00:05:30,750
Most of these only last a few hours.

134
00:05:30,750 --> 00:05:32,880
In the case of like a sports event,

135
00:05:32,880 --> 00:05:33,840
we need to know right away

136
00:05:33,840 --> 00:05:35,820
whether we have a problem with an origin,

137
00:05:35,820 --> 00:05:36,780
whether it's CloudFront

138
00:05:36,780 --> 00:05:39,210
or if we're using something
like DRM or advertising,

139
00:05:39,210 --> 00:05:41,520
whether there's a problem with
that affecting our stream.

140
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:43,320
So dashboards are the
first line of defense,

141
00:05:43,320 --> 00:05:45,670
so we know where to look,
where to dive deeper.

142
00:05:46,740 --> 00:05:48,290
Just speaking of diving deeper,

143
00:05:49,710 --> 00:05:52,080
CloudFront, it supports
real time access logs.

144
00:05:52,080 --> 00:05:53,130
And as you can see here,

145
00:05:53,130 --> 00:05:56,040
it actually uses Amazon
Kinesis to deliver this.

146
00:05:56,040 --> 00:05:58,660
It's delivering realtime
logs for millions of viewers,

147
00:05:58,660 --> 00:06:00,420
which is extremely difficult.

148
00:06:00,420 --> 00:06:03,120
Kinesis is designed exactly for this.

149
00:06:03,120 --> 00:06:06,000
So when you configure
realtime logs in CloudFront,

150
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:07,590
it's gonna ask for a Kinesis endpoint.

151
00:06:07,590 --> 00:06:09,090
And the nice thing about Kinesis

152
00:06:09,090 --> 00:06:11,070
is you can have multiple consumers

153
00:06:11,070 --> 00:06:13,230
pulling that data in parallel.

154
00:06:13,230 --> 00:06:15,570
So we can have realtime dashboards,

155
00:06:15,570 --> 00:06:20,570
we can have observability
platforms, analytics platforms.

156
00:06:21,246 --> 00:06:24,270
We can also share this data
in real time with partners,

157
00:06:24,270 --> 00:06:26,250
whether they're looking
at viewership in real time

158
00:06:26,250 --> 00:06:28,770
or they're looking at advertising data

159
00:06:28,770 --> 00:06:31,500
and they need that
information in real time.

160
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:33,180
So then with this real time data,

161
00:06:33,180 --> 00:06:35,700
we can see issues before
they become a big problem

162
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:36,570
and react to it.

163
00:06:36,570 --> 00:06:38,649
And we can adjust our platform
in real time as needed

164
00:06:38,649 --> 00:06:40,803
to handle these largest events.

165
00:06:42,570 --> 00:06:44,887
Then lastly, access logs.

166
00:06:44,887 --> 00:06:47,237
These are stored in batches on S3.

167
00:06:47,237 --> 00:06:50,523
As you can see here, the delay
is usually in the minutes.

168
00:06:52,530 --> 00:06:54,810
Nice thing about S3 is we can...

169
00:06:54,810 --> 00:06:56,220
We can tie Athena into it

170
00:06:56,220 --> 00:06:59,130
so we can query all these
logs using standard SQL.

171
00:06:59,130 --> 00:07:01,530
And we can set life
cycles on the S3 bucket.

172
00:07:01,530 --> 00:07:05,490
So we can have events from
weeks or even years ago

173
00:07:05,490 --> 00:07:07,078
stored in archival.

174
00:07:07,078 --> 00:07:10,710
So we can compare this previous event

175
00:07:10,710 --> 00:07:13,620
to one that we did, you know,
maybe a week or a month ago,

176
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:14,940
and see how we've improved

177
00:07:14,940 --> 00:07:17,250
and find out lessons learned.

178
00:07:17,250 --> 00:07:19,080
We can do some
troubleshooting after the fact

179
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:21,380
and we can pull reporting
easily using Athena.

180
00:07:23,190 --> 00:07:25,261
And then lastly, console reports.

181
00:07:25,261 --> 00:07:28,140
This is in the CloudFront console

182
00:07:28,140 --> 00:07:29,610
and is useful for just, you know,

183
00:07:29,610 --> 00:07:31,321
figuring out trends, viewership,

184
00:07:31,321 --> 00:07:35,490
cache fill ratio between
events and monthly reports.

185
00:07:35,490 --> 00:07:37,240
So that's always available as well.

186
00:07:39,180 --> 00:07:40,530
Okay.

187
00:07:40,530 --> 00:07:44,379
Next, I spoke a lot about
CloudFront and its logs.

188
00:07:44,379 --> 00:07:46,770
But typically CloudFront only has access

189
00:07:46,770 --> 00:07:50,639
to things that are in the
HTTP header or geo information

190
00:07:50,639 --> 00:07:53,340
such as the user agent,

191
00:07:53,340 --> 00:07:55,827
the client's IP address,
maybe the geo region,

192
00:07:55,827 --> 00:07:58,050
the ASN, cache status.

193
00:07:58,050 --> 00:07:59,880
And this has always been logged,

194
00:07:59,880 --> 00:08:02,940
whether it's in real time
logs or in the S3 logs.

195
00:08:02,940 --> 00:08:05,610
But I mentioned earlier about the client.

196
00:08:05,610 --> 00:08:08,729
The client has a lot of
really valuable information

197
00:08:08,729 --> 00:08:10,650
such as like the throughput.

198
00:08:10,650 --> 00:08:15,650
The client being the player
like dash.js or hls.js,

199
00:08:16,140 --> 00:08:17,790
it's making decisions

200
00:08:17,790 --> 00:08:19,800
about which video bit rate to pull

201
00:08:19,800 --> 00:08:24,060
based on what it knows your
home internet bandwidth is.

202
00:08:24,060 --> 00:08:25,564
And having that kind of information

203
00:08:25,564 --> 00:08:27,720
along with session ID and content ID

204
00:08:27,720 --> 00:08:31,230
is extremely valuable for
figuring out what's going on.

205
00:08:31,230 --> 00:08:34,062
But in the past, this
information was only available

206
00:08:34,062 --> 00:08:36,900
using like SDKs from third parties,

207
00:08:36,900 --> 00:08:40,350
and it was sending it using
beacons to some other platform.

208
00:08:40,350 --> 00:08:43,710
So you had CloudFront or
CDN logs in one bucket,

209
00:08:43,710 --> 00:08:46,170
then you had all the player
information in another bucket,

210
00:08:46,170 --> 00:08:48,330
and really no way to tie the two together.

211
00:08:48,330 --> 00:08:51,509
And trust me it's extremely
difficult to do that.

212
00:08:51,509 --> 00:08:53,550
It can be done but it's not easy.

213
00:08:53,550 --> 00:08:54,510
But what if there were a way

214
00:08:54,510 --> 00:08:56,970
to combine all this client information

215
00:08:56,970 --> 00:08:59,814
such as you know, the bit rate
being used, the session ID,

216
00:08:59,814 --> 00:09:01,135
which rendition,

217
00:09:01,135 --> 00:09:04,230
whether it's HD or standard
definition content,

218
00:09:04,230 --> 00:09:07,320
and combine that with all the information

219
00:09:07,320 --> 00:09:08,460
that CloudFront knows about,

220
00:09:08,460 --> 00:09:13,050
such as HTTP headers, you
know, user agent IP address.

221
00:09:13,050 --> 00:09:16,320
And that's exactly what CMCD,
Common Media Client Data

222
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:17,153
attempts to solve.

223
00:09:17,153 --> 00:09:20,520
It's actually a standard now
that was created by CTA Wave,

224
00:09:20,520 --> 00:09:22,050
which has created a lot of other standards

225
00:09:22,050 --> 00:09:23,910
that Jamie's gonna talk about later,

226
00:09:23,910 --> 00:09:26,010
that pretty much all CDNs adhere to

227
00:09:26,010 --> 00:09:28,110
and the players know about.

228
00:09:28,110 --> 00:09:30,378
So using CMCD, all this information...

229
00:09:30,378 --> 00:09:32,520
(audience applauds)

230
00:09:32,520 --> 00:09:34,740
All this information is
kept in the same log line.

231
00:09:34,740 --> 00:09:36,900
So all this content ID, session ID,

232
00:09:36,900 --> 00:09:39,870
is transmitted as query
strings or headers to the CDN.

233
00:09:39,870 --> 00:09:40,980
And since it's standardized,

234
00:09:40,980 --> 00:09:43,020
we know what to do with it already.

235
00:09:43,020 --> 00:09:44,449
And a lot of partners

236
00:09:44,449 --> 00:09:46,305
that you might be using
for a monitoring platform

237
00:09:46,305 --> 00:09:48,333
already know how to deal with CMCD.

238
00:09:51,300 --> 00:09:54,543
So CloudFront has supported
CMCD for quite a while.

239
00:09:55,830 --> 00:09:57,012
If you look here on the left,

240
00:09:57,012 --> 00:09:59,430
this is a realtime log configuration.

241
00:09:59,430 --> 00:10:01,170
You can see here, we
have additional fields

242
00:10:01,170 --> 00:10:03,150
that are standard CMCD fields.

243
00:10:03,150 --> 00:10:05,340
They're all prefixed with CMCD.

244
00:10:05,340 --> 00:10:07,920
And you can just choose
some of them or all of them

245
00:10:07,920 --> 00:10:09,660
depending on what your client's sending.

246
00:10:09,660 --> 00:10:12,572
And all this information will
be added to the realtime logs

247
00:10:12,572 --> 00:10:14,730
that we're sending through to Kinesis.

248
00:10:14,730 --> 00:10:16,599
And again, a lot of partners
already support this

249
00:10:16,599 --> 00:10:18,930
on their logging platforms.

250
00:10:18,930 --> 00:10:20,880
And we actually have a reference sample

251
00:10:20,880 --> 00:10:21,713
that already knows

252
00:10:21,713 --> 00:10:23,160
how to deal with this
additional information

253
00:10:23,160 --> 00:10:24,090
in the log lines.

254
00:10:24,090 --> 00:10:25,840
And it has a realtime dashboard

255
00:10:26,760 --> 00:10:28,448
that actually refreshes in real time

256
00:10:28,448 --> 00:10:29,640
based on all this data

257
00:10:29,640 --> 00:10:31,080
to show exactly what's happening

