or just search for the video observability

261
00:10:38,023 --> 00:10:40,170
with CMCD and CloudFront,

262
00:10:40,170 --> 00:10:41,850
and try it out on your own distribution

263
00:10:41,850 --> 00:10:44,493
being a reference sample
that's free to use,

264
00:10:45,870 --> 00:10:48,070
and you can edit it at
Willow's open source.

265
00:10:49,109 --> 00:10:49,942
(coughs)

266
00:10:49,942 --> 00:10:50,775
Excuse me.

267
00:10:50,775 --> 00:10:51,608
So it is easy.

268
00:10:51,608 --> 00:10:52,530
CMCD is easy.

269
00:10:52,530 --> 00:10:55,530
Again, you saw it on the realtime logs.

270
00:10:55,530 --> 00:10:57,261
In CloudFront, it's just
adding those additional fills

271
00:10:57,261 --> 00:10:59,220
and having a consumer dashboard

272
00:10:59,220 --> 00:11:01,200
that knows how to access it.

273
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:02,160
This is an example

274
00:11:02,160 --> 00:11:05,010
on some of the players
you might be using today.

275
00:11:05,010 --> 00:11:06,900
These are two popular open source players,

276
00:11:06,900 --> 00:11:09,780
hls.js and dash.js.

277
00:11:09,780 --> 00:11:11,343
And as you can see here,

278
00:11:12,270 --> 00:11:13,220
configuring CMCD

279
00:11:13,220 --> 00:11:16,560
is just a matter of adding
a few more key value pairs

280
00:11:16,560 --> 00:11:19,380
when you instantiate your player.

281
00:11:19,380 --> 00:11:20,910
In the case of hls.js,

282
00:11:20,910 --> 00:11:22,833
which is one I'm very familiar with,

283
00:11:22,833 --> 00:11:25,350
it's just a CMCD structure.

284
00:11:25,350 --> 00:11:27,840
But notice specifically on the left,

285
00:11:27,840 --> 00:11:29,040
we have a session ID now.

286
00:11:29,040 --> 00:11:34,040
That's actually a common
or standard CMCD field,

287
00:11:34,230 --> 00:11:35,850
which is extremely useful.

288
00:11:35,850 --> 00:11:39,210
If you are using CMCD and
not using session ID today,

289
00:11:39,210 --> 00:11:40,950
how I suggest you do it,

290
00:11:40,950 --> 00:11:41,783
that's usually pulled

291
00:11:41,783 --> 00:11:43,620
from like your content management system

292
00:11:43,620 --> 00:11:46,389
for that particular user
when they start a session.

293
00:11:46,389 --> 00:11:48,930
When you include this
session ID in a field,

294
00:11:48,930 --> 00:11:51,390
you actually can find all the logs

295
00:11:51,390 --> 00:11:52,890
that are tied to a specific user.

296
00:11:52,890 --> 00:11:54,960
So you can see individual user's journey

297
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:57,690
from starting to playback
your stream till end.

298
00:11:57,690 --> 00:11:59,610
How many times they switched bit rates,

299
00:11:59,610 --> 00:12:01,770
rebuffered, stalled, all that.

300
00:12:01,770 --> 00:12:04,830
So you can figure out
individual user journeys

301
00:12:04,830 --> 00:12:08,220
and use the same information

302
00:12:08,220 --> 00:12:11,790
to find other users' journeys
as well based on session ID,

303
00:12:11,790 --> 00:12:13,170
which wasn't possible before

304
00:12:13,170 --> 00:12:16,380
since the client information
and the CD information

305
00:12:16,380 --> 00:12:18,180
were stored in separate locations,

306
00:12:18,180 --> 00:12:19,480
so it makes it super easy.

307
00:12:21,840 --> 00:12:24,690
Okay, so now this is
security requirements.

308
00:12:24,690 --> 00:12:26,013
We talked about logging.

309
00:12:26,850 --> 00:12:27,750
We've vetted visibility

310
00:12:27,750 --> 00:12:29,700
to our CloudFront distribution.

311
00:12:29,700 --> 00:12:31,890
We wanna make sure all of our users,

312
00:12:31,890 --> 00:12:35,820
our valid users are receiving
the best possible experience.

313
00:12:35,820 --> 00:12:39,990
But we don't want our invalid users

314
00:12:39,990 --> 00:12:41,691
that are trying to steal our streams,

315
00:12:41,691 --> 00:12:43,170
take down our...

316
00:12:43,170 --> 00:12:45,720
You know, steal our content
or take down our streams.

317
00:12:45,720 --> 00:12:48,660
We really wanna stop them
from receiving our content

318
00:12:48,660 --> 00:12:50,790
and harming the experience

319
00:12:50,790 --> 00:12:53,463
that other users are experiencing.

320
00:12:55,290 --> 00:12:57,390
So what do these users look like?

321
00:12:57,390 --> 00:12:59,236
Well, ideally in a perfect world

322
00:12:59,236 --> 00:13:01,360
you'd have your origin
server behind CloudFront,

323
00:13:01,360 --> 00:13:04,620
you'd have CloudFront
delivering a standard URL,

324
00:13:04,620 --> 00:13:07,500
in this case it's HLS and index.m3u8.

325
00:13:07,500 --> 00:13:10,410
And all of your paid or subscribed users

326
00:13:10,410 --> 00:13:11,613
would pull the content.

327
00:13:12,570 --> 00:13:14,223
That's not the case, as we all know.

328
00:13:14,223 --> 00:13:17,940
We see users that are trying
to re-stream the content.

329
00:13:17,940 --> 00:13:19,740
So they're a paid valid user

330
00:13:19,740 --> 00:13:21,390
coming from maybe a particular IP address,

331
00:13:21,390 --> 00:13:23,790
pulling our content and then
re-streaming it to their users

332
00:13:23,790 --> 00:13:25,240
who are probably paying them.

333
00:13:26,100 --> 00:13:27,633
Obviously, we don't want that.

334
00:13:28,710 --> 00:13:30,423
And then invalid regions.

335
00:13:32,130 --> 00:13:34,830
Not only have we not really
designed our infrastructure

336
00:13:34,830 --> 00:13:37,879
to maybe operate in a different country

337
00:13:37,879 --> 00:13:40,105
for scalability purposes,

338
00:13:40,105 --> 00:13:42,303
when we have viewers from invalid regions,

339
00:13:42,303 --> 00:13:43,710
they're messing up our stats.

340
00:13:43,710 --> 00:13:45,540
So they might be having a bad experience

341
00:13:45,540 --> 00:13:48,900
and it's going to mess up
our analysis of how our...

342
00:13:48,900 --> 00:13:51,300
You know, whether our
event was a success or not.

343
00:13:51,300 --> 00:13:53,430
If we see viewers coming
from outside of the country

344
00:13:53,430 --> 00:13:54,840
with high latency numbers,

345
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:58,290
that's gonna affect all of our reporting.

346
00:13:58,290 --> 00:13:59,372
And then lastly,

347
00:13:59,372 --> 00:14:01,920
Jes is gonna talk about it in a little bit

348
00:14:01,920 --> 00:14:03,690
with rights holders.

349
00:14:03,690 --> 00:14:05,220
There might be even legal consequences

350
00:14:05,220 --> 00:14:07,590
of delivering content
outside of your country

351
00:14:07,590 --> 00:14:10,140
where your contract states

352
00:14:10,140 --> 00:14:11,910
that you can only deliver
in a certain region,

353
00:14:11,910 --> 00:14:14,850
you only have rights to deliver
in maybe a specific state.

354
00:14:14,850 --> 00:14:17,800
In the case of sporting events
or maybe a specific country.

355
00:14:19,050 --> 00:14:21,161
I know in the past dealing
with some customers

356
00:14:21,161 --> 00:14:22,860
when the Olympics are involved,

357
00:14:22,860 --> 00:14:25,800
the contract for theirs
is extremely specific

358
00:14:25,800 --> 00:14:28,170
when it comes to regions

359
00:14:28,170 --> 00:14:31,200
and the security required
to deliver that content.

360
00:14:31,200 --> 00:14:34,110
So again, rights holders
are very important as well.

361
00:14:34,110 --> 00:14:35,670
And then lastly, unpaid users

362
00:14:35,670 --> 00:14:37,620
that have found the way around
any CloudFront restrictions

363
00:14:37,620 --> 00:14:40,350
and are able to go directly to the origin.

364
00:14:40,350 --> 00:14:42,270
So obviously, we don't want that,

365
00:14:42,270 --> 00:14:44,030
but also if you're able to
go directly to the origin,

366
00:14:44,030 --> 00:14:46,710
it's going to affect the
experience of everybody

367
00:14:46,710 --> 00:14:49,290
'cause the origin should be
protected behind CloudFront,

368
00:14:49,290 --> 00:14:50,880
where CloudFront serves

369
00:14:50,880 --> 00:14:53,430
99 plus percent of the
traffic from its cache.

370
00:14:53,430 --> 00:14:54,300
So the origin server

371
00:14:54,300 --> 00:14:56,500
should never be delivering
content directly.

372
00:14:58,555 --> 00:15:00,933
Okay, so what tools do
we have available to us?

373
00:15:02,010 --> 00:15:04,500
So first of all, my son, he's seven.

374
00:15:04,500 --> 00:15:06,349
He's actually been home
from school recently

375
00:15:06,349 --> 00:15:09,000
on vacation for break.

376
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,770
And he tends to find ways

377
00:15:10,770 --> 00:15:12,767
to stream YouTube when
he is not supposed to.

378
00:15:12,767 --> 00:15:17,220
So I've tried the firewall
rules on my home internet.

379
00:15:17,220 --> 00:15:20,490
And eventually ended up
just locking the remotes

380
00:15:20,490 --> 00:15:22,410
in the office and networks.

381
00:15:22,410 --> 00:15:23,520
So that's the tools I have.

382
00:15:23,520 --> 00:15:24,690
But obviously on CloudFront

383
00:15:24,690 --> 00:15:26,940
we don't have physical locking keys,

384
00:15:26,940 --> 00:15:30,390
but we do have some ways
to restrict traffic.

385
00:15:30,390 --> 00:15:31,650
So first off,

386
00:15:31,650 --> 00:15:33,600
for anybody that's been
in the CloudFront console,

387
00:15:33,600 --> 00:15:36,150
you've probably noticed the
geo restrictions built in.

388
00:15:36,150 --> 00:15:38,335
So that's just built into the
distribution in the console

389
00:15:38,335 --> 00:15:40,830
through the API if you're using that.

390
00:15:40,830 --> 00:15:42,442
So this is a way

391
00:15:42,442 --> 00:15:45,090
to quickly allow or
disallow specific regions.

392
00:15:45,090 --> 00:15:47,187
So if I'm delivering content

393
00:15:47,187 --> 00:15:48,480
that's only allowed

394
00:15:48,480 --> 00:15:50,670
to be delivered in the
United States, for instance.

395
00:15:50,670 --> 00:15:51,990
I can go into CloudFront

396
00:15:51,990 --> 00:15:55,410
and quickly add geo restrictions
to only allow the US,

397
00:15:55,410 --> 00:15:59,253
or I could block specific
countries within there.

398
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:02,550
But the next layer we
can add on top of that,

399
00:16:02,550 --> 00:16:03,870
the next tool in our tool chain

400
00:16:03,870 --> 00:16:06,813
is AWS Web Application Firewall, WAF.

401
00:16:08,070 --> 00:16:10,860
So in this case, we can
inspect anything coming in,

402
00:16:10,860 --> 00:16:12,993
whether it's headers, IP addresses,

403
00:16:14,100 --> 00:16:16,590
against a list.

404
00:16:16,590 --> 00:16:18,960
And we also have lists
that you can subscribe to.

405
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:20,040
So we have to manage lists.

406
00:16:20,040 --> 00:16:24,030
So we're already able to
allow specific regions

407
00:16:24,030 --> 00:16:24,870
with geo restrictions,

408
00:16:24,870 --> 00:16:26,220
but what about users who are using

409
00:16:26,220 --> 00:16:29,610
maybe VPNs or proxies
to access our stream?

410
00:16:29,610 --> 00:16:31,080
Using WAF, we can actually subscribe

411
00:16:31,080 --> 00:16:32,880
the list of known VPN endpoints,

412
00:16:32,880 --> 00:16:34,680
known proxy endpoints.

413
00:16:34,680 --> 00:16:36,990
Or in the case of the re-streamer,

414
00:16:36,990 --> 00:16:39,960
we found there that our IP address,

415
00:16:39,960 --> 00:16:42,000
in the case of the example was 1, 2, 3, 4.

416
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:44,640
During the event, we can
actually add that IP address

417
00:16:44,640 --> 00:16:45,630
to our own managed list

418
00:16:45,630 --> 00:16:47,630
to block that user that's a re-streamer.

419
00:16:48,780 --> 00:16:51,990
So WAF is really useful for
before, during, and after event.

420
00:16:51,990 --> 00:16:53,910
So if you notice something specific,

421
00:16:53,910 --> 00:16:56,580
you can add rules after the
fact for your next event.

422
00:16:56,580 --> 00:16:57,990
Or in the case of the re-streamer,

423
00:16:57,990 --> 00:17:00,930
you can actually modify
it during the event.

424
00:17:00,930 --> 00:17:01,763
And then lastly,

425
00:17:01,763 --> 00:17:04,740
for anything above and beyond
geo restrictions and WAF,

426
00:17:04,740 --> 00:17:06,090
we have functions.

427
00:17:06,090 --> 00:17:07,350
So CloudFront functions

428
00:17:07,350 --> 00:17:09,330
run as JavaScript
actually on the ad server.

429
00:17:09,330 --> 00:17:12,900
They're extremely low
latency and high performant.

430
00:17:12,900 --> 00:17:14,880
And you're able to analyze the request

431
00:17:14,880 --> 00:17:18,360
and/or responses coming from CloudFront

432
00:17:18,360 --> 00:17:19,950
or to and from the origin.

433
00:17:19,950 --> 00:17:22,560
And we've added key value stores as well.

434
00:17:22,560 --> 00:17:25,179
So you're able to add data
to the key value store

435
00:17:25,179 --> 00:17:26,550
using the API

436
00:17:26,550 --> 00:17:28,350
and query that on edge function.

437
00:17:28,350 --> 00:17:29,760
So we're gonna go into detail

438
00:17:29,760 --> 00:17:31,020
about what this can be used for

439
00:17:31,020 --> 00:17:32,920
when it comes to security in a minute.

440
00:17:35,460 --> 00:17:37,023
So how do we secure our origin?

441
00:17:38,880 --> 00:17:41,091
So as we all know, CloudFront
is origin agnostic.

442
00:17:41,091 --> 00:17:44,160
So the origin could be anywhere, really.

443
00:17:44,160 --> 00:17:46,620
So first off, if our origin is on-prem,

444
00:17:46,620 --> 00:17:48,240
it's most likely on a public subnet.

445
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:51,320
So we obviously don't want
users to access that directly

446
00:17:51,320 --> 00:17:54,180
so that again, it affects
the experience for everybody.

447
00:17:54,180 --> 00:17:55,950
So the first thing we can do

448
00:17:55,950 --> 00:17:57,687
is when you configure
your origin in CloudFront,

449
00:17:57,687 --> 00:17:59,610
you can leverage HTTP headers.

450
00:17:59,610 --> 00:18:00,750
That's then the origin level.

451
00:18:00,750 --> 00:18:03,390
You can send a secret
header to the origin,

452
00:18:03,390 --> 00:18:04,560
which the origin can validate

453
00:18:04,560 --> 00:18:07,140
that this is actually in
fact coming from CloudFront.

454
00:18:07,140 --> 00:18:07,973
And then you can also...

455
00:18:07,973 --> 00:18:08,880
We also publish a list

456
00:18:08,880 --> 00:18:11,250
of known IP addresses of
CloudFront edge servers

457
00:18:11,250 --> 00:18:12,930
that you can add to your firewall on-prem

458
00:18:12,930 --> 00:18:14,130
or on the origin itself

459
00:18:14,130 --> 00:18:17,220
to allow only CloudFront to access it.

460
00:18:17,220 --> 00:18:18,063
And then second,

461
00:18:19,110 --> 00:18:21,330
if you're using something like
an application load balancer

462
00:18:21,330 --> 00:18:22,380
or network load balancer,

463
00:18:22,380 --> 00:18:25,833
maybe EC2 instances behind
those for your origin,

464
00:18:26,786 --> 00:18:29,130
CloudFront now can leverage VPC Origins.

465
00:18:29,130 --> 00:18:31,440
I don't know if everybody's aware of that.

466
00:18:31,440 --> 00:18:33,973
And recently we've even
introduced cross region...

467
00:18:33,973 --> 00:18:35,190
Cross account, sorry.

468
00:18:35,190 --> 00:18:37,050
Cross account VPC Origins.

469
00:18:37,050 --> 00:18:38,880
So if you're using multiple accounts,

470
00:18:38,880 --> 00:18:40,530
CloudFront can access these origins

471
00:18:40,530 --> 00:18:42,197
on a VPC from other accounts,

472
00:18:42,197 --> 00:18:46,200
whether your accounts or
even partners' accounts,

473
00:18:46,200 --> 00:18:47,033
which is huge,

474
00:18:47,033 --> 00:18:48,871
'cause if your origin's not
even on a public subnet,

475
00:18:48,871 --> 00:18:51,330
it can't be accessed in the first place.

476
00:18:51,330 --> 00:18:52,260
And then lastly,

477
00:18:52,260 --> 00:18:54,210
for some of our managed
services delivery media,

478
00:18:54,210 --> 00:18:56,586
a lot of you use S3 for live
and on-demand media delivery

479
00:18:56,586 --> 00:19:00,030
as well as elemental media package.

480
00:19:00,030 --> 00:19:02,130
These can use origin access control.

481
00:19:02,130 --> 00:19:03,750
So those are rule sets

482
00:19:03,750 --> 00:19:05,610
that specifically allow only CloudFront

483
00:19:05,610 --> 00:19:09,003
to access the content using signed URLs.

484
00:19:10,740 --> 00:19:12,780
So I mentioned functions to take...

485
00:19:12,780 --> 00:19:14,181
To basically expand upon security

486
00:19:14,181 --> 00:19:18,259
above and beyond WAF and geo restrictions.

487
00:19:18,259 --> 00:19:23,259
We see a lot of customers use
tokenization within functions

488
00:19:23,540 --> 00:19:25,080
to further secure content.

489
00:19:25,080 --> 00:19:26,043
So a token,

490
00:19:27,306 --> 00:19:29,670
it's actually typically we see JWT used,

491
00:19:29,670 --> 00:19:31,200
but there's quite a few formats out there.

492
00:19:31,200 --> 00:19:32,550
And using functions, we're flexible.

493
00:19:32,550 --> 00:19:33,600
You can basically implement

494
00:19:33,600 --> 00:19:36,750
any sort of function
mechanism that you'd like,

495
00:19:36,750 --> 00:19:39,460
whether it's JWT or some custom function

496
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:43,650
or some custom token that
you use across other CDNs.

497
00:19:43,650 --> 00:19:46,853
So inside the token it
basically describes who you are,

498
00:19:46,853 --> 00:19:49,920
what you're able to
watch, like a content ID,

499
00:19:49,920 --> 00:19:51,390
and it would have a time limit.

500
00:19:51,390 --> 00:19:53,190
So in case of JWT,

501
00:19:53,190 --> 00:19:54,600
it's very easy to set a lifetime

502
00:19:54,600 --> 00:19:55,620
that this token's only valid

503
00:19:55,620 --> 00:19:58,320
for an hour, two hours, a full day.

504
00:19:58,320 --> 00:20:00,270
And then it also provides,

505
00:20:00,270 --> 00:20:03,570
you know, instructions on
where and what you can watch.

506
00:20:03,570 --> 00:20:06,210
So ideally a user with a valid token,

507
00:20:06,210 --> 00:20:07,890
they're sending all
this header information

508
00:20:07,890 --> 00:20:09,840
and IP address information
in the CloudFront.

509
00:20:09,840 --> 00:20:12,111
We're able to look up
their geo information

510
00:20:12,111 --> 00:20:13,620
using geo headers,

511
00:20:13,620 --> 00:20:15,402
they're configuring CloudFront.

512
00:20:15,402 --> 00:20:17,070
And the token contains
all this information,

513
00:20:17,070 --> 00:20:19,980
that they're able to watch
from a specific maybe US state,

514
00:20:19,980 --> 00:20:21,240
that they're tied

515
00:20:21,240 --> 00:20:23,820
to this particular IP
address or user agent.

516
00:20:23,820 --> 00:20:25,650
And the function is
gonna validate all this

517
00:20:25,650 --> 00:20:28,620
against the token and what
CloudFront knows about the user.

518
00:20:28,620 --> 00:20:29,880
And if everything matches up,

519
00:20:29,880 --> 00:20:32,901
the token wasn't modified
in transit from the user,

520
00:20:32,901 --> 00:20:34,380
and the token hasn't expired,

521
00:20:34,380 --> 00:20:37,233
then we just return a 200
OK within the function.

522
00:20:39,180 --> 00:20:41,002
And then we have users
with invalid tokens.

523
00:20:41,002 --> 00:20:42,270
Maybe they modify...

524
00:20:42,270 --> 00:20:43,530
They tried to modify their token

525
00:20:43,530 --> 00:20:44,490
and create their own token

526
00:20:44,490 --> 00:20:47,220
and it's invalid 'cause
that wasn't signed correctly

527
00:20:47,220 --> 00:20:50,130
or they're coming from
an invalid location.

528
00:20:50,130 --> 00:20:52,702
You know, they may be
traveled with a valid token,

529
00:20:52,702 --> 00:20:54,338
we signed it for their home use

530
00:20:54,338 --> 00:20:57,030
on their cellular network

531
00:20:57,030 --> 00:20:58,950
and they didn't receive a new token.

532
00:20:58,950 --> 00:21:00,000
We'll actually return back

533
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:03,780
