534
00:21:03,780 --> 00:21:04,860
from the function itself

535
00:21:04,860 --> 00:21:06,210
and immediately deny that user

536
00:21:06,210 --> 00:21:08,960
before they even hit CloudFront
in their origin server.

537
00:21:10,170 --> 00:21:12,780
And then lastly, we have a
user here with a share token.

538
00:21:12,780 --> 00:21:15,180
Again, all these examples are using JWT,

539
00:21:15,180 --> 00:21:16,470
which is really common,

540
00:21:16,470 --> 00:21:18,840
which is easily implemented in functions.

541
00:21:18,840 --> 00:21:20,160
This user has a shared token,

542
00:21:20,160 --> 00:21:23,220
so they received the valid
token from the first user

543
00:21:23,220 --> 00:21:24,870
and they're trying to reuse it,

544
00:21:24,870 --> 00:21:26,940
and they might be living
in the same neighborhood

545
00:21:26,940 --> 00:21:27,990
and using the same device,

546
00:21:27,990 --> 00:21:30,660
so it happens to be valid for some reason.

547
00:21:30,660 --> 00:21:32,143
But we noticed that this user...

548
00:21:32,143 --> 00:21:34,992
This token is being used multiple
times and it's not valid.

549
00:21:34,992 --> 00:21:37,590
We can actually add this token value

550
00:21:37,590 --> 00:21:38,880
into the key value store.

551
00:21:38,880 --> 00:21:40,440
So that's for us at a good use case

552
00:21:40,440 --> 00:21:44,190
for key value stores and
functions is token revocation.

553
00:21:44,190 --> 00:21:46,590
So you can insert this
token into a key value store

554
00:21:46,590 --> 00:21:48,240
when you notice something wrong with it,

555
00:21:48,240 --> 00:21:49,950
and it's just being used too many times.

556
00:21:49,950 --> 00:21:52,500
And then you can have the
function return a 403 forbidden

557
00:21:52,500 --> 00:21:55,080
if that token's in that key value store.

558
00:21:55,080 --> 00:21:58,020
So again, this is a common
use case that we see

559
00:21:58,020 --> 00:22:00,840
for tokenization JWT tokens.

