00:23:41,010 --> 00:23:43,383
for a talk on last mile capacity.

603
00:23:45,780 --> 00:23:47,190
- So large scale...

604
00:23:47,190 --> 00:23:48,023
Large scale events

605
00:23:48,023 --> 00:23:49,831
can generate significant
internet traffic spikes

606
00:23:49,831 --> 00:23:51,840
over a really short period of time,

607
00:23:51,840 --> 00:23:53,370
with strained network links

608
00:23:53,370 --> 00:23:55,503
that connect viewers to end content.

609
00:23:56,430 --> 00:23:57,660
However, there might actually

610
00:23:57,660 --> 00:23:59,010
only be a certain amount of capacity

611
00:23:59,010 --> 00:24:01,950
between an internet exchange itself

612
00:24:01,950 --> 00:24:04,470
and an ISP or a smaller city.

613
00:24:04,470 --> 00:24:07,770
For example, ISPs continuously
optimize their networks,

614
00:24:07,770 --> 00:24:09,510
but scaling capacity

615
00:24:09,510 --> 00:24:11,760
for like those last minute big events

616
00:24:11,760 --> 00:24:13,610
is understandably challenging, right?

617
00:24:14,490 --> 00:24:15,570
Especially those events

618
00:24:15,570 --> 00:24:17,010
that you know, you only need that capacity

619
00:24:17,010 --> 00:24:18,510
for that short period of time.

620
00:24:19,560 --> 00:24:22,467
When a network becomes
saturated or congested,

621
00:24:22,467 --> 00:24:26,160
both packet loss and
increased latencies can occur.

622
00:24:26,160 --> 00:24:27,750
And a result on the viewer experience

623
00:24:27,750 --> 00:24:30,360
is things like quality drops, rebuffering,

624
00:24:30,360 --> 00:24:32,013
or even those playback failures.

625
00:24:32,940 --> 00:24:35,610
Remember, you can lean on
that monitoring approach

626
00:24:35,610 --> 00:24:36,810
that John spoke about earlier

627
00:24:36,810 --> 00:24:39,570
to try and help you identify
some of these issues.

628
00:24:39,570 --> 00:24:41,310
But unless you own the network

629
00:24:41,310 --> 00:24:44,040
or the underlying network
as an ATT provider,

630
00:24:44,040 --> 00:24:44,873
this is something

631
00:24:44,873 --> 00:24:46,850
that is really largely
out of your control.

632
00:24:51,330 --> 00:24:52,350
Last year, however,

633
00:24:52,350 --> 00:24:54,480
we introduced Embedded POPs.

634
00:24:54,480 --> 00:24:55,740
And they overcome this challenge

635
00:24:55,740 --> 00:24:58,170
by getting you closer
to those end viewers,

636
00:24:58,170 --> 00:25:00,366
caching content directly
inside an ISP network,

637
00:25:00,366 --> 00:25:03,630
and removing some of the
dependency on the network links

638
00:25:03,630 --> 00:25:06,720
between the viewers and
the internet exchange.

639
00:25:06,720 --> 00:25:08,700
If you didn't see it
on the POP map before,

640
00:25:08,700 --> 00:25:12,240
we've got over 1,140 embedded POPs

641
00:25:12,240 --> 00:25:16,440
across over a hundred ISPs
in more than 20 countries.

642
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:20,400
Because that distance to end
viewers is reduced further,

643
00:25:20,400 --> 00:25:21,870
customers have already...

644
00:25:21,870 --> 00:25:24,030
Customers that already
adopted in embedded POPs

645
00:25:24,030 --> 00:25:26,193
have seen performance improvements too.

646
00:25:29,970 --> 00:25:32,610
Because we're able to remove
some of the network dependency,

647
00:25:32,610 --> 00:25:35,060
they're really great for
highly cachable content.

648
00:25:35,940 --> 00:25:37,140
So we are very focused

649
00:25:37,140 --> 00:25:39,330
on the media and entertainment
space today, obviously.

650
00:25:39,330 --> 00:25:40,590
But you can also use them

651
00:25:40,590 --> 00:25:42,630
for things like or
content like game delivery

652
00:25:42,630 --> 00:25:44,223
and also software downloads.

653
00:25:45,840 --> 00:25:48,510
So as part of the
onboarding of Embedded POPs,

654
00:25:48,510 --> 00:25:51,870
we validate the workflow that
you want to use them for.

655
00:25:51,870 --> 00:25:53,421
If it is a good fit,

656
00:25:53,421 --> 00:25:57,150
the distribution is enabled
up by us in the backend.

657
00:25:57,150 --> 00:26:00,300
However, there is some additional
work required on your side

658
00:26:00,300 --> 00:26:01,890
to make sure your client application

659
00:26:01,890 --> 00:26:04,110
can route to Embedded POPs.

660
00:26:04,110 --> 00:26:05,520
The way that we recommend doing this

661
00:26:05,520 --> 00:26:08,190
is integrating the client routing SDK

662
00:26:08,190 --> 00:26:10,023
into your URL vending service.

663
00:26:12,630 --> 00:26:13,980
So how does this work?

664
00:26:13,980 --> 00:26:16,110
Well firstly, you need
to do that integration

665
00:26:16,110 --> 00:26:19,950
of that client routing SDK
into your Euro vending service.

666
00:26:19,950 --> 00:26:21,300
The QR code on the bottom right

667
00:26:21,300 --> 00:26:24,540
is actually the link
to that SDK in GitHub,

668
00:26:24,540 --> 00:26:27,480
if you're interested in
having a look at that.

669
00:26:27,480 --> 00:26:29,010
So when the client application

670
00:26:29,010 --> 00:26:31,680
requests a URL from that vending service,

671
00:26:31,680 --> 00:26:32,760
the client in...

672
00:26:32,760 --> 00:26:35,850
The client IP is encoded into the URL,

673
00:26:35,850 --> 00:26:38,553
and it's annotated a CR
label in this diagram.

674
00:26:40,230 --> 00:26:43,347
The client then performs a DNS lookup,

675
00:26:43,347 --> 00:26:45,360
and Route53 and CloudFront

676
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:50,280
is able to decode that client
IP from that CR label itself.

677
00:26:50,280 --> 00:26:52,530
Then CloudFront returns the best POP

678
00:26:52,530 --> 00:26:54,300
based on that client IP.

679
00:26:54,300 --> 00:26:56,550
Whether that's an embedded
POP if appropriate

680
00:26:56,550 --> 00:26:57,843
or a traditional POP.

681
00:26:59,160 --> 00:27:02,110
The client can then start
fetching content from CloudFront.

682
00:27:02,970 --> 00:27:06,630
So in summary, embedded
POPs deliver cached content

683
00:27:06,630 --> 00:27:08,520
directly from ISP networks,

684
00:27:08,520 --> 00:27:09,570
improving performance

685
00:27:09,570 --> 00:27:10,710
and overcoming

686
00:27:10,710 --> 00:27:13,590
those potential last
mile capacity constraints

687
00:27:13,590 --> 00:27:15,090
that you might have.

688
00:27:15,090 --> 00:27:17,190
If you want to make use of embedded POPs,

689
00:27:17,190 --> 00:27:19,680
I really urge you to
contact your account team

690
00:27:19,680 --> 00:27:20,670
to help you validate...

691
00:27:20,670 --> 00:27:23,043
Evaluate your workload
to see if it's suitable.

692
00:27:25,740 --> 00:27:29,040
So typically, the next bottleneck
that we see is the origin.

693
00:27:29,040 --> 00:27:29,873
Our aim really

694
00:27:29,873 --> 00:27:33,180
is to offload as much traffic
as possible from the origin

695
00:27:33,180 --> 00:27:37,140
so it has enough capacity
to serve requests at scale.

696
00:27:37,140 --> 00:27:38,460
This is to prevent our origin

697
00:27:38,460 --> 00:27:40,810
from becoming overwhelmed
and failing entirely.

698
00:27:45,660 --> 00:27:47,160
Caching helps with this, of course.

699
00:27:47,160 --> 00:27:48,602
And CloudFront uses tiered caching.

700
00:27:48,602 --> 00:27:50,760
So we have edge locations,

701
00:27:50,760 --> 00:27:52,770
we have regional edge caches,

702
00:27:52,770 --> 00:27:54,780
but you can also use
something called Origin Shield

703
00:27:54,780 --> 00:27:57,840
to further reduce that origin load.

704
00:27:57,840 --> 00:28:01,083
Instead of regional edge caches
hitting the origin directly,

705
00:28:02,670 --> 00:28:04,590
they go through Origin Shield,

706
00:28:04,590 --> 00:28:07,290
and this provides a
better cache hit ratio,

707
00:28:07,290 --> 00:28:09,510
reducing demand on your origin,

708
00:28:09,510 --> 00:28:11,460
especially for those events,

709
00:28:11,460 --> 00:28:13,210
you know, we've got a lot of scale.

710
00:28:18,540 --> 00:28:20,190
So we've covered capacity,

711
00:28:20,190 --> 00:28:21,870
we've covered reducing load

712
00:28:21,870 --> 00:28:25,890
and ensuring viewers can
get a great experience.

