intervention might be required.

788
00:31:35,370 --> 00:31:37,740
So we have the same
architecture as what we had,

789
00:31:37,740 --> 00:31:39,390
but obviously we've got
region one and region two

790
00:31:39,390 --> 00:31:42,030
with Media Connect, Media
Live, and Media Package.

791
00:31:42,030 --> 00:31:43,110
But we also have the addition

792
00:31:43,110 --> 00:31:45,630
of Elemental Live or AWS Elemental Live,

793
00:31:45,630 --> 00:31:48,750
which is our on-prem encoding appliance,

794
00:31:48,750 --> 00:31:49,583
which in our case

795
00:31:49,583 --> 00:31:51,603
is doing that venue contribution encoding.

796
00:31:53,910 --> 00:31:55,380
So let's say something goes wrong

797
00:31:55,380 --> 00:31:59,490
with one of the contribution
feeds going to region one

798
00:31:59,490 --> 00:32:02,550
where the viewers are
currently streaming from.

799
00:32:02,550 --> 00:32:05,760
Well, viewers connected to that

800
00:32:05,760 --> 00:32:07,170
might start seeing black frames

801
00:32:07,170 --> 00:32:09,783
instead of the actual video
content or real content.

802
00:32:10,650 --> 00:32:12,289
But hopefully you've got a real...

803
00:32:12,289 --> 00:32:14,760
An eyes on glass operations team

804
00:32:14,760 --> 00:32:16,890
and they spot this issue early on

805
00:32:16,890 --> 00:32:19,110
and decide that they
want to do that failover

806
00:32:19,110 --> 00:32:20,940
to region two manually.

807
00:32:20,940 --> 00:32:22,410
Remember, there's a time delay, right?

808
00:32:22,410 --> 00:32:24,720
Between the issue occurring,

809
00:32:24,720 --> 00:32:26,070
somebody spotting it,

810
00:32:26,070 --> 00:32:30,693
and then also proactively
rectifying that situation.

811
00:32:32,460 --> 00:32:35,910
So the failover occurs,

812
00:32:35,910 --> 00:32:39,240
our viewers go to the URL vending service

813
00:32:39,240 --> 00:32:41,430
and say I need a new URL,

814
00:32:41,430 --> 00:32:43,323
and it returns one for region two.

815
00:32:44,790 --> 00:32:46,110
However, there's a few challenges here

816
00:32:46,110 --> 00:32:47,490
to kind of think about.

817
00:32:47,490 --> 00:32:49,620
Number one, predominantly,
is the, you know,

818
00:32:49,620 --> 00:32:52,770
it requires somebody
manually to do this, right?

819
00:32:52,770 --> 00:32:53,910
And there's also a time delay

820
00:32:53,910 --> 00:32:57,093
in detecting and then remediating it.

821
00:32:58,170 --> 00:33:00,480
But not only that, when a viewer rejoins,

822
00:33:00,480 --> 00:33:01,770
are they gonna have to go find

823
00:33:01,770 --> 00:33:04,110
where they were viewing
in a stream, for example?

824
00:33:04,110 --> 00:33:05,970
And then the timing might be misaligned

825
00:33:05,970 --> 00:33:07,320
between the two anyway,

826
00:33:07,320 --> 00:33:08,403
two regions anyway.

827
00:33:09,240 --> 00:33:10,590
So how do you keep things in sync?

828
00:33:10,590 --> 00:33:12,873
How do you do these things automatically?

829
00:33:13,710 --> 00:33:14,880
So we're gonna explore this further,

830
00:33:14,880 --> 00:33:16,920
but we're gonna start with time code.

831
00:33:16,920 --> 00:33:18,210
Time code is time reference

832
00:33:18,210 --> 00:33:19,860
that's embedded in each video frame.

833
00:33:19,860 --> 00:33:21,000
Time code can be really important

834
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:23,033
in the media distribution world.

835
00:33:23,033 --> 00:33:24,520
We want to use it for synchronization

836
00:33:24,520 --> 00:33:28,170
in downstream components such
as the encoder and packager

837
00:33:28,170 --> 00:33:31,050
to provide that frame accurate alignment.

838
00:33:31,050 --> 00:33:33,060
So time code is part of the answer,

839
00:33:33,060 --> 00:33:35,910
but how is it actually applied
to a failover scenario?

840
00:33:35,910 --> 00:33:37,620
We have a feature that
can help manage this

841
00:33:37,620 --> 00:33:40,350
and it's called seamless
cross region failover.

842
00:33:40,350 --> 00:33:42,180
So we are gonna start with

843
00:33:42,180 --> 00:33:44,580
the elemental live encoder on-prem.

844
00:33:44,580 --> 00:33:46,710
And that's gonna use the
same time code source,

845
00:33:46,710 --> 00:33:50,670
so both regions receive an
aligned contribution feed.

846
00:33:50,670 --> 00:33:53,340
Media live is then
configured with Epoch locking

847
00:33:53,340 --> 00:33:54,630
and uses the embedded timekeeper,

848
00:33:54,630 --> 00:33:57,150
that timing source being that input lock.

849
00:33:57,150 --> 00:34:00,327
And then CMAF ingests on the
output media package into...

850
00:34:00,327 --> 00:34:02,340
Intermediate package, sorry.

851
00:34:02,340 --> 00:34:05,160
And when you combine CMAF
ingest and Epoch locking,

852
00:34:05,160 --> 00:34:07,560
it results in this regular
segmentation cadence

853
00:34:07,560 --> 00:34:09,450
based on the Epoch time.

854
00:34:09,450 --> 00:34:11,790
Media package can then use
stainless synchronization

855
00:34:11,790 --> 00:34:14,553
to help predictably
package the output content.

856
00:34:17,490 --> 00:34:19,230
So what happens if
something does go wrong,

857
00:34:19,230 --> 00:34:21,420
such as slate input, incomplete manifesto,

858
00:34:21,420 --> 00:34:22,650
and a missing DRM key?

859
00:34:22,650 --> 00:34:24,150
Well, media package
actually has the ability

860
00:34:24,150 --> 00:34:25,360
to 404 its endpoint.

861
00:34:25,360 --> 00:34:27,120
And CloudFront is configured

862
00:34:27,120 --> 00:34:28,530
with something called Origin Groups

863
00:34:28,530 --> 00:34:31,470
where you specify a
primary and a secondary,

864
00:34:31,470 --> 00:34:35,073
and also fail level criteria
based on HTTP status code.

865
00:34:35,940 --> 00:34:38,370
When it picks up the media package

866
00:34:38,370 --> 00:34:40,950
has indeed 404 to one
of its origin endpoints,

867
00:34:40,950 --> 00:34:44,370
it'll automatically send that
traffic to the secondary.

868
00:34:44,370 --> 00:34:45,295
But what if

869
00:34:45,295 --> 00:34:47,010
it's not such a fundamental
problem, for example?

870
00:34:47,010 --> 00:34:50,455
What if it's black frames,
frozen frames in the source

871
00:34:50,455 --> 00:34:53,340
and it's only impacting one
of those contribution reads

872
00:34:53,340 --> 00:34:54,900
going into one of the regions?

873
00:34:54,900 --> 00:34:56,430
Well, building on the
previous architecture,

874
00:34:56,430 --> 00:34:57,300
we have a capability

875
00:34:57,300 --> 00:34:59,489
called Media Quality Aware
Resiliency to solve this,

876
00:34:59,489 --> 00:35:00,903
or MQAR.

877
00:35:02,340 --> 00:35:03,840
So Media Live actually has the ability

878
00:35:03,840 --> 00:35:06,630
to also produce something
called an MQCS score

879
00:35:06,630 --> 00:35:07,463
on each segment.

880
00:35:07,463 --> 00:35:10,290
And MQCS stands for Media
Quality Confidence Score.

881
00:35:10,290 --> 00:35:12,030
And that's based on those input parameters

882
00:35:12,030 --> 00:35:15,278
of being black frame detection,
frozen frame detection,

883
00:35:15,278 --> 00:35:16,830
or input source loss.

884
00:35:16,830 --> 00:35:19,230
And that score is out of a hundred.

885
00:35:19,230 --> 00:35:22,680
And each score is independently
based on its own input.

886
00:35:22,680 --> 00:35:24,150
Media package actually has the ability

887
00:35:24,150 --> 00:35:25,710
to use this in two locations.

888
00:35:25,710 --> 00:35:27,030
It's able to use it on the input

889
00:35:27,030 --> 00:35:29,043
to provide in-region failover,

890
00:35:30,210 --> 00:35:34,830
and also on its output via CMSD

891
00:35:34,830 --> 00:35:36,660
or Common Media Server Data.

892
00:35:36,660 --> 00:35:39,340
John spoke about CMCD earlier,

893
00:35:39,340 --> 00:35:41,823
CMSD is also part of that CTA spec.

894
00:35:43,650 --> 00:35:45,300
And then finally,

895
00:35:45,300 --> 00:35:48,380
continue to use origin
groups on CloudFront.

896
00:35:48,380 --> 00:35:50,040
But instead of it being default,

897
00:35:50,040 --> 00:35:52,150
we use Media Quality Score

898
00:35:53,490 --> 00:35:56,880
being the origin selection
criteria, instead of the default.

899
00:35:56,880 --> 00:35:57,713
The way it works

900
00:35:57,713 --> 00:36:00,330
is there's a getting ahead
request into both regions.

901
00:36:00,330 --> 00:36:02,100
And it basically picks the segment

902
00:36:02,100 --> 00:36:03,540
that's gonna ultimately provide

903
00:36:03,540 --> 00:36:06,630
that better viewing experience
to interviewers or clients.

